    "blueprint": "## Visual Style\n**Theme: `dark`** — a deep-space backdrop best supports a 3D black hole scene (accretion disk glow, starfield, and high-contrast light-bending paths).\n\n**Palette (semantic roles)**\n- **backgroundSpace:** `#050814` (near-black blue for space)\n- **primaryDisk:** `#ff7a18` (hot orange for inner accretion disk)\n- **secondaryDisk:** `#ffd166` (warm yellow for outer disk highlights)\n- **lensingLight:** `#6ee7ff` (cyan for photon/light-ray paths)\n- **warningHorizon:** `#ff3b3b` (red for event horizon / “point of no return” boundary)\n\n## Learning Goal\nUnderstand that a black hole is defined by an **event horizon** where escape becomes impossible, and that intense gravity causes **orbital motion, accretion heating, and gravitational lensing** of light.\n\n## Analogy\n**“A deep whirlpool in glowing water.”**  \nThe black hole is the drain (event horizon), the accretion disk is glowing swirling water heating up as it spirals in, and light rays are floating “sticks” that curve as they pass the whirlpool.\n\n## Simulation Variables\n| Name | Label | Min | Max | Default | Unit |\n|---|---|---:|---:|---:|---|\n| blackHoleMass | Black Hole Mass | 1 | 50 | 15 | arbitrary |\n| spin | Spin (Rotation) | 0 | 0.99 | 0.6 | dimensionless |\n| diskDensity | Accretion Disk Density | 0 | 1 | 0.55 | dimensionless |\n| cameraDistance | Camera Distance | 5 | 35 | 18 | scene units |\n| photonCount | Light Rays (Photon Paths) | 0 | 300 | 120 | count |\n\n## Scaffolding Steps\n1. **Instruction:** Set **Black Hole Mass** to around **5–10**, and slowly orbit the camera around the black hole.  \n   **Concept:** Identify key structures: dark center, event horizon boundary, disk around it.  \n   **Condition:** `blackHoleMass >= 5 && blackHoleMass <= 10`\n\n2. **Instruction:** Increase **Black Hole Mass** to **30+** and watch the light rays near the black hole.  \n   **Concept:** Stronger gravity increases **gravitational lensing** (light bends more, can arc around).  \n   **Condition:** `blackHoleMass >= 30`\n\n3. **Instruction:** Raise **Light Rays (Photon Paths)** to **200+** and look for rays that loop partially around the black hole before escaping.  \n   **Concept:** Near the black hole, some light can enter near-orbiting trajectories (photon-sphere-like behavior) before exiting.  \n   **Condition:** `photonCount >= 200`\n\n4. **Instruction:** Increase **Accretion Disk Density** above **0.75** and observe how the disk brightness and thickness change as it spirals inward.  \n   **Concept:** Accretion disks get hotter/brighter as matter compresses and speeds up—energy is released before crossing the horizon.  \n   **Condition:** `diskDensity >= 0.75`\n\n5. **Instruction:** Increase **Spin** above **0.85** and compare the disk motion and asymmetry (one side appearing brighter).  \n   **Concept:** Spin introduces strong rotational effects (frame-dragging feel) and produces **relativistic beaming**: the side rotating toward you appears brighter.  \n   **Condition:** `spin >= 0.85`"
